4929#ifndef CURL_DISABLE_PROXY
4930/****************************************************************
4931* Checks if the host is in the noproxy list. returns true if it matches
4932* and therefore the proxy should NOT be used.
4933****************************************************************/
4934static bool check_noproxy(const char *name, const char *no_proxy)
4935{
4936 /* no_proxy=domain1.dom,host.domain2.dom
4937 * (a comma-separated list of hosts which should
4938 * not be proxied, or an asterisk to override
4939 * all proxy variables)
4940 */
4941 size_t tok_start;
4942 size_t tok_end;
4943 const char *separator = ", ";
4944 size_t no_proxy_len;
4945 size_t namelen;
4946 char *endptr;
4947
4948 if(no_proxy && no_proxy[0]) {
4949 if(strcasecompare("*", no_proxy)) {
4950 return TRUE;
4951 }
4952
4953 /* NO_PROXY was specified and it wasn't just an asterisk */
4954
4955 no_proxy_len = strlen(no_proxy);
4956 endptr = strchr(name, ':');
4957 if(endptr)
4958 namelen = endptr - name;
4959 else
4960 namelen = strlen(name);
4961
4962 for(tok_start = 0; tok_start < no_proxy_len; tok_start = tok_end + 1) {
4963 while(tok_start < no_proxy_len &&
4964 strchr(separator, no_proxy[tok_start]) != NULL) {
4965 /* Look for the beginning of the token. */
4966 ++tok_start;
4967 }
4968
4969 if(tok_start == no_proxy_len)
4970 break; /* It was all trailing separator chars, no more tokens. */
4971
4972 for(tok_end = tok_start; tok_end < no_proxy_len &&
4973 strchr(separator, no_proxy[tok_end]) == NULL; ++tok_end)
4974 /* Look for the end of the token. */
4975 ;
4976
4977 /* To match previous behaviour, where it was necessary to specify
4978 * ".local.com" to prevent matching "notlocal.com", we will leave
4979 * the '.' off.
4980 */
4981 if(no_proxy[tok_start] == '.')
4982 ++tok_start;
4983
4984 if((tok_end - tok_start) <= namelen) {
4985 /* Match the last part of the name to the domain we are checking. */
4986 const char *checkn = name + namelen - (tok_end - tok_start);
4987 if(strncasecompare(no_proxy + tok_start, checkn,
4988 tok_end - tok_start)) {
4989 if((tok_end - tok_start) == namelen || *(checkn - 1) == '.') {
4990 /* We either have an exact match, or the previous character is a .
4991 * so it is within the same domain, so no proxy for this host.
4992 */
4993 return TRUE;
4994 }
4995 }
4996 } /* if((tok_end - tok_start) <= namelen) */
4997 } /* for(tok_start = 0; tok_start < no_proxy_len;
4998 tok_start = tok_end + 1) */
4999 } /* NO_PROXY was specified and it wasn't just an asterisk */
5000
5001 return FALSE;
5002}
5003
5004#ifndef CURL_DISABLE_HTTP
5005/****************************************************************
5006* Detect what (if any) proxy to use. Remember that this selects a host
5007* name and is not limited to HTTP proxies only.
5008* The returned pointer must be freed by the caller (unless NULL)
5009****************************************************************/
5010static char *detect_proxy(struct connectdata *conn)
5011{
5012 char *proxy = NULL;
5013
5014 /* If proxy was not specified, we check for default proxy environment
5015 * variables, to enable i.e Lynx compliance:
5016 *
5017 * http_proxy=http://some.server.dom:port/
5018 * https_proxy=http://some.server.dom:port/
5019 * ftp_proxy=http://some.server.dom:port/
5020 * no_proxy=domain1.dom,host.domain2.dom
5021 * (a comma-separated list of hosts which should
5022 * not be proxied, or an asterisk to override
5023 * all proxy variables)
5024 * all_proxy=http://some.server.dom:port/
5025 * (seems to exist for the CERN www lib. Probably
5026 * the first to check for.)
5027 *
5028 * For compatibility, the all-uppercase versions of these variables are
5029 * checked if the lowercase versions don't exist.
5030 */
5031 char proxy_env[128];
5032 const char *protop = conn->handler->scheme;
5033 char *envp = proxy_env;
5034 char *prox;
5035
5036 /* Now, build <protocol>_proxy and check for such a one to use */
5037 while(*protop)
5038 *envp++ = (char)tolower((int)*protop++);
5039
5040 /* append _proxy */
5041 strcpy(envp, "_proxy");
5042
5043 /* read the protocol proxy: */
5044 prox = curl_getenv(proxy_env);
5045
5046 /*
5047 * We don't try the uppercase version of HTTP_PROXY because of
5048 * security reasons:
5049 *
5050 * When curl is used in a webserver application
5051 * environment (cgi or php), this environment variable can
5052 * be controlled by the web server user by setting the
5053 * http header 'Proxy:' to some value.
5054 *
5055 * This can cause 'internal' http/ftp requests to be
5056 * arbitrarily redirected by any external attacker.
5057 */
5058 if(!prox && !strcasecompare("http_proxy", proxy_env)) {
5059 /* There was no lowercase variable, try the uppercase version: */
5060 Curl_strntoupper(proxy_env, proxy_env, sizeof(proxy_env));
5061 prox = curl_getenv(proxy_env);
5062 }
5063
5064 if(prox)
5065 proxy = prox; /* use this */
5066 else {
5067 proxy = curl_getenv("all_proxy"); /* default proxy to use */
5068 if(!proxy)
5069 proxy = curl_getenv("ALL_PROXY");
5070 }
5071
5072 return proxy;
5073}
5074#endif /* CURL_DISABLE_HTTP */
5075
5076/*
5077 * If this is supposed to use a proxy, we need to figure out the proxy
5078 * host name, so that we can re-use an existing connection
5079 * that may exist registered to the same proxy host.
5080 */
5081static CURLcode parse_proxy(struct Curl_easy *data,
5082 struct connectdata *conn, char *proxy,
5083 curl_proxytype proxytype)
5084{
5085 char *prox_portno;
5086 char *endofprot;
5087
5088 /* We use 'proxyptr' to point to the proxy name from now on... */
5089 char *proxyptr;
5090 char *portptr;
5091 char *atsign;
5092 long port = -1;
5093 char *proxyuser = NULL;
5094 char *proxypasswd = NULL;
5095 bool sockstype;
5096
5097 /* We do the proxy host string parsing here. We want the host name and the
5098 * port name. Accept a protocol:// prefix
5099 */
5100
5101 /* Parse the protocol part if present */
5102 endofprot = strstr(proxy, "://");
5103 if(endofprot) {
5104 proxyptr = endofprot + 3;
5105 if(checkprefix("https", proxy))
5106 proxytype = CURLPROXY_HTTPS;
5107 else if(checkprefix("socks5h", proxy))
5108 proxytype = CURLPROXY_SOCKS5_HOSTNAME;
5109 else if(checkprefix("socks5", proxy))
5110 proxytype = CURLPROXY_SOCKS5;
5111 else if(checkprefix("socks4a", proxy))
5112 proxytype = CURLPROXY_SOCKS4A;
5113 else if(checkprefix("socks4", proxy) || checkprefix("socks", proxy))
5114 proxytype = CURLPROXY_SOCKS4;
5115 else if(checkprefix("http:", proxy))
5116 ; /* leave it as HTTP or HTTP/1.0 */
5117 else {
5118 /* Any other xxx:// reject! */
5119 failf(data, "Unsupported proxy scheme for \'%s\'", proxy);
5120 return CURLE_COULDNT_CONNECT;
5121 }
5122 }
5123 else
5124 proxyptr = proxy; /* No xxx:// head: It's a HTTP proxy */
5125
5126#ifdef USE_SSL
5127 if(!Curl_ssl->support_https_proxy)
5128#endif
5129 if(proxytype == CURLPROXY_HTTPS) {
5130 failf(data, "Unsupported proxy \'%s\', libcurl is built without the "
5131 "HTTPS-proxy support.", proxy);
5132 return CURLE_NOT_BUILT_IN;
5133 }
5134
5135 sockstype = proxytype == CURLPROXY_SOCKS5_HOSTNAME ||
5136 proxytype == CURLPROXY_SOCKS5 ||
5137 proxytype == CURLPROXY_SOCKS4A ||
5138 proxytype == CURLPROXY_SOCKS4;
5139
5140 /* Is there a username and password given in this proxy url? */
5141 atsign = strchr(proxyptr, '@');
5142 if(atsign) {
5143 CURLcode result =
5144 parse_login_details(proxyptr, atsign - proxyptr,
5145 &proxyuser, &proxypasswd, NULL);
5146 if(result)
5147 return result;
5148 proxyptr = atsign + 1;
5149 }
5150
5151 /* start scanning for port number at this point */
5152 portptr = proxyptr;
5153
5154 /* detect and extract RFC6874-style IPv6-addresses */
5155 if(*proxyptr == '[') {
5156 char *ptr = ++proxyptr; /* advance beyond the initial bracket */
5157 while(*ptr && (ISXDIGIT(*ptr) || (*ptr == ':') || (*ptr == '.')))
5158 ptr++;
5159 if(*ptr == '%') {
5160 /* There might be a zone identifier */
5161 if(strncmp("%25", ptr, 3))
5162 infof(data, "Please URL encode %% as %%25, see RFC 6874.\n");
5163 ptr++;
5164 /* Allow unreserved characters as defined in RFC 3986 */
5165 while(*ptr && (ISALPHA(*ptr) || ISXDIGIT(*ptr) || (*ptr == '-') ||
5166 (*ptr == '.') || (*ptr == '_') || (*ptr == '~')))
5167 ptr++;
5168 }
5169 if(*ptr == ']')
5170 /* yeps, it ended nicely with a bracket as well */
5171 *ptr++ = 0;
5172 else
5173 infof(data, "Invalid IPv6 address format\n");
5174 portptr = ptr;
5175 /* Note that if this didn't end with a bracket, we still advanced the
5176 * proxyptr first, but I can't see anything wrong with that as no host
5177 * name nor a numeric can legally start with a bracket.
5178 */
5179 }
5180
5181 /* Get port number off proxy.server.com:1080 */
5182 prox_portno = strchr(portptr, ':');
5183 if(prox_portno) {
5184 char *endp = NULL;
5185
5186 *prox_portno = 0x0; /* cut off number from host name */
5187 prox_portno ++;
5188 /* now set the local port number */
5189 port = strtol(prox_portno, &endp, 10);
5190 if((endp && *endp && (*endp != '/') && (*endp != ' ')) ||
5191 (port < 0) || (port > 65535)) {
5192 /* meant to detect for example invalid IPv6 numerical addresses without
5193 brackets: "2a00:fac0:a000::7:13". Accept a trailing slash only
5194 because we then allow "URL style" with the number followed by a
5195 slash, used in curl test cases already. Space is also an acceptable
5196 terminating symbol. */
5197 infof(data, "No valid port number in proxy string (%s)\n",
5198 prox_portno);
5199 }
5200 else
5201 conn->port = port;
5202 }
5203 else {
5204 if(proxyptr[0]=='/') {
5205 /* If the first character in the proxy string is a slash, fail
5206 immediately. The following code will otherwise clear the string which
5207 will lead to code running as if no proxy was set! */
5208 Curl_safefree(proxyuser);
5209 Curl_safefree(proxypasswd);
5210 return CURLE_COULDNT_RESOLVE_PROXY;
5211 }
5212
5213 /* without a port number after the host name, some people seem to use
5214 a slash so we strip everything from the first slash */
5215 atsign = strchr(proxyptr, '/');
5216 if(atsign)
5217 *atsign = '\0'; /* cut off path part from host name */
5218
5219 if(data->set.proxyport)
5220 /* None given in the proxy string, then get the default one if it is
5221 given */
5222 port = data->set.proxyport;
5223 else {
5224 if(proxytype == CURLPROXY_HTTPS)
5225 port = CURL_DEFAULT_HTTPS_PROXY_PORT;
5226 else
5227 port = CURL_DEFAULT_PROXY_PORT;
5228 }
5229 }
5230
5231 if(*proxyptr) {
5232 struct proxy_info *proxyinfo =
5233 sockstype ? &conn->socks_proxy : &conn->http_proxy;
5234 proxyinfo->proxytype = proxytype;
5235
5236 if(proxyuser) {
5237 /* found user and password, rip them out. note that we are unescaping
5238 them, as there is otherwise no way to have a username or password
5239 with reserved characters like ':' in them. */
5240 Curl_safefree(proxyinfo->user);
5241 proxyinfo->user = curl_easy_unescape(data, proxyuser, 0, NULL);
5242 Curl_safefree(proxyuser);
5243
5244 if(!proxyinfo->user) {
5245 Curl_safefree(proxypasswd);
5246 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5247 }
5248
5249 Curl_safefree(proxyinfo->passwd);
5250 if(proxypasswd && strlen(proxypasswd) < MAX_CURL_PASSWORD_LENGTH)
5251 proxyinfo->passwd = curl_easy_unescape(data, proxypasswd, 0, NULL);
5252 else
5253 proxyinfo->passwd = strdup("");
5254 Curl_safefree(proxypasswd);
5255
5256 if(!proxyinfo->passwd)
5257 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5258
5259 conn->bits.proxy_user_passwd = TRUE; /* enable it */
5260 }
5261
5262 if(port >= 0) {
5263 proxyinfo->port = port;
5264 if(conn->port < 0 || sockstype || !conn->socks_proxy.host.rawalloc)
5265 conn->port = port;
5266 }
5267
5268 /* now, clone the cleaned proxy host name */
5269 Curl_safefree(proxyinfo->host.rawalloc);
5270 proxyinfo->host.rawalloc = strdup(proxyptr);
5271 proxyinfo->host.name = proxyinfo->host.rawalloc;
5272
5273 if(!proxyinfo->host.rawalloc)
5274 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5275 }
5276
5277 Curl_safefree(proxyuser);
5278 Curl_safefree(proxypasswd);
5279
5280 return CURLE_OK;
5281}

5283/*
5284 * Extract the user and password from the authentication string
5285 */
5286static CURLcode parse_proxy_auth(struct Curl_easy *data,
5287 struct connectdata *conn)
5288{
5289 char proxyuser[MAX_CURL_USER_LENGTH]="";
5290 char proxypasswd[MAX_CURL_PASSWORD_LENGTH]="";
5291 CURLcode result;
5292
5293 if(data->set.str[STRING_PROXYUSERNAME] != NULL) {
5294 strncpy(proxyuser, data->set.str[STRING_PROXYUSERNAME],
5295 MAX_CURL_USER_LENGTH);
5296 proxyuser[MAX_CURL_USER_LENGTH-1] = '\0'; /*To be on safe side*/
5297 }
5298 if(data->set.str[STRING_PROXYPASSWORD] != NULL) {
5299 strncpy(proxypasswd, data->set.str[STRING_PROXYPASSWORD],
5300 MAX_CURL_PASSWORD_LENGTH);
5301 proxypasswd[MAX_CURL_PASSWORD_LENGTH-1] = '\0'; /*To be on safe side*/
5302 }
5303
5304 result = Curl_urldecode(data, proxyuser, 0, &conn->http_proxy.user, NULL,
5305 FALSE);
5306 if(!result)
5307 result = Curl_urldecode(data, proxypasswd, 0, &conn->http_proxy.passwd,
5308 NULL, FALSE);
5309 return result;
5310}
5311
5312/* create_conn helper to parse and init proxy values. to be called after unix
5313 socket init but before any proxy vars are evaluated. */
5314static CURLcode create_conn_helper_init_proxy(struct connectdata *conn)
5315{
5316 char *proxy = NULL;
5317 char *socksproxy = NULL;
5318 char *no_proxy = NULL;
5319 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
5320 struct Curl_easy *data = conn->data;
5321
5322 /*************************************************************
5323 * Extract the user and password from the authentication string
5324 *************************************************************/
5325 if(conn->bits.proxy_user_passwd) {
5326 result = parse_proxy_auth(data, conn);
5327 if(result)
5328 goto out;
5329 }
5330
5331 /*************************************************************
5332 * Detect what (if any) proxy to use
5333 *************************************************************/
5334 if(data->set.str[STRING_PROXY]) {
5335 proxy = strdup(data->set.str[STRING_PROXY]);
5336 /* if global proxy is set, this is it */
5337 if(NULL == proxy) {
5338 failf(data, "memory shortage");
5339 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5340 goto out;
5341 }
5342 }
5343
5344 if(data->set.str[STRING_PRE_PROXY]) {
5345 socksproxy = strdup(data->set.str[STRING_PRE_PROXY]);
5346 /* if global socks proxy is set, this is it */
5347 if(NULL == socksproxy) {
5348 failf(data, "memory shortage");
5349 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5350 goto out;
5351 }
5352 }
5353
5354 if(!data->set.str[STRING_NOPROXY]) {
5355 no_proxy = curl_getenv("no_proxy");
5356 if(!no_proxy)
5357 no_proxy = curl_getenv("NO_PROXY");
5358 }
5359
5360 if(check_noproxy(conn->host.name, data->set.str[STRING_NOPROXY] ?
5361 data->set.str[STRING_NOPROXY] : no_proxy)) {
5362 Curl_safefree(proxy);
5363 Curl_safefree(socksproxy);
5364 }
5365#ifndef CURL_DISABLE_HTTP
5366 else if(!proxy && !socksproxy)
5367 /* if the host is not in the noproxy list, detect proxy. */
5368 proxy = detect_proxy(conn);
5369#endif /* CURL_DISABLE_HTTP */
5370
5371 Curl_safefree(no_proxy);
5372
5373#ifdef USE_UNIX_SOCKETS
5374 /* For the time being do not mix proxy and unix domain sockets. See #1274 */
5375 if(proxy && conn->unix_domain_socket) {
5376 free(proxy);
5377 proxy = NULL;
5378 }
5379#endif
5380
5381 if(proxy && (!*proxy || (conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_NONETWORK))) {
5382 free(proxy); /* Don't bother with an empty proxy string or if the
5383 protocol doesn't work with network */
5384 proxy = NULL;
5385 }
5386 if(socksproxy && (!*socksproxy ||
5387 (conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_NONETWORK))) {
5388 free(socksproxy); /* Don't bother with an empty socks proxy string or if
5389 the protocol doesn't work with network */
5390 socksproxy = NULL;
5391 }
5392
5393 /***********************************************************************
5394 * If this is supposed to use a proxy, we need to figure out the proxy host
5395 * name, proxy type and port number, so that we can re-use an existing
5396 * connection that may exist registered to the same proxy host.
5397 ***********************************************************************/
5398 if(proxy || socksproxy) {
5399 if(proxy) {
5400 result = parse_proxy(data, conn, proxy, conn->http_proxy.proxytype);
5401 Curl_safefree(proxy); /* parse_proxy copies the proxy string */
5402 if(result)
5403 goto out;
5404 }
5405
5406 if(socksproxy) {
5407 result = parse_proxy(data, conn, socksproxy,
5408 conn->socks_proxy.proxytype);
5409 /* parse_proxy copies the socks proxy string */
5410 Curl_safefree(socksproxy);
5411 if(result)
5412 goto out;
5413 }
5414
5415 if(conn->http_proxy.host.rawalloc) {
5416#ifdef CURL_DISABLE_HTTP
5417 /* asking for a HTTP proxy is a bit funny when HTTP is disabled... */
5418 result = CURLE_UNSUPPORTED_PROTOCOL;
5419 goto out;
5420#else
5421 /* force this connection's protocol to become HTTP if compatible */
5422 if(!(conn->handler->protocol & PROTO_FAMILY_HTTP)) {
5423 if((conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_PROXY_AS_HTTP) &&
5424 !conn->bits.tunnel_proxy)
5425 conn->handler = &Curl_handler_http;
5426 else
5427 /* if not converting to HTTP over the proxy, enforce tunneling */
5428 conn->bits.tunnel_proxy = TRUE;
5429 }
5430 conn->bits.httpproxy = TRUE;
5431#endif
5432 }
5433 else {
5434 conn->bits.httpproxy = FALSE; /* not a HTTP proxy */
5435 conn->bits.tunnel_proxy = FALSE; /* no tunneling if not HTTP */
5436 }
5437
5438 if(conn->socks_proxy.host.rawalloc) {
5439 if(!conn->http_proxy.host.rawalloc) {
5440 /* once a socks proxy */
5441 if(!conn->socks_proxy.user) {
5442 conn->socks_proxy.user = conn->http_proxy.user;
5443 conn->http_proxy.user = NULL;
5444 Curl_safefree(conn->socks_proxy.passwd);
5445 conn->socks_proxy.passwd = conn->http_proxy.passwd;
5446 conn->http_proxy.passwd = NULL;
5447 }
5448 }
5449 conn->bits.socksproxy = TRUE;
5450 }
5451 else
5452 conn->bits.socksproxy = FALSE; /* not a socks proxy */
5453 }
5454 else {
5455 conn->bits.socksproxy = FALSE;
5456 conn->bits.httpproxy = FALSE;
5457 }
5458 conn->bits.proxy = conn->bits.httpproxy || conn->bits.socksproxy;
5459
5460 if(!conn->bits.proxy) {
5461 /* we aren't using the proxy after all... */
5462 conn->bits.proxy = FALSE;
5463 conn->bits.httpproxy = FALSE;
5464 conn->bits.socksproxy = FALSE;
5465 conn->bits.proxy_user_passwd = FALSE;
5466 conn->bits.tunnel_proxy = FALSE;
5467 }
5468
5469out:
5470
5471 free(socksproxy);
5472 free(proxy);
5473 return result;
5474}
5475#endif /* CURL_DISABLE_PROXY */
5476
5477/*
5478 * parse_url_login()
5479 *
5480 * Parse the login details (user name, password and options) from the URL and
5481 * strip them out of the host name
5482 *
5483 * Inputs: data->set.use_netrc (CURLOPT_NETRC)
5484 * conn->host.name
5485 *
5486 * Outputs: (almost :- all currently undefined)
5487 * conn->bits.user_passwd - non-zero if non-default passwords exist
5488 * user - non-zero length if defined
5489 * passwd - non-zero length if defined
5490 * options - non-zero length if defined
5491 * conn->host.name - remove user name and password
5492 */
5493static CURLcode parse_url_login(struct Curl_easy *data,
5494 struct connectdata *conn,
5495 char **user, char **passwd, char **options)
5496{
5497 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
5498 char *userp = NULL;
5499 char *passwdp = NULL;
5500 char *optionsp = NULL;
5501
5502 /* At this point, we're hoping all the other special cases have
5503 * been taken care of, so conn->host.name is at most
5504 * [user[:password][;options]]@]hostname
5505 *
5506 * We need somewhere to put the embedded details, so do that first.
5507 */
5508
5509 char *ptr = strchr(conn->host.name, '@');
5510 char *login = conn->host.name;
5511
5512 DEBUGASSERT(!**user);
5513 DEBUGASSERT(!**passwd);
5514 DEBUGASSERT(!**options);
5515 DEBUGASSERT(conn->handler);
5516
5517 if(!ptr)
5518 goto out;
5519
5520 /* We will now try to extract the
5521 * possible login information in a string like:
5522 * ftp://user:password@ftp.my.site:8021/README */
5523 conn->host.name = ++ptr;
5524
5525 /* So the hostname is sane. Only bother interpreting the
5526 * results if we could care. It could still be wasted
5527 * work because it might be overtaken by the programmatically
5528 * set user/passwd, but doing that first adds more cases here :-(
5529 */
5530
5531 if(data->set.use_netrc == CURL_NETRC_REQUIRED)
5532 goto out;
5533
5534 /* We could use the login information in the URL so extract it. Only parse
5535 options if the handler says we should. */
5536 result = parse_login_details(login, ptr - login - 1,
5537 &userp, &passwdp,
5538 (conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_URLOPTIONS)?
5539 &optionsp:NULL);
5540 if(result)
5541 goto out;
5542
5543 if(userp) {
5544 char *newname;
5545
5546 /* We have a user in the URL */
5547 conn->bits.userpwd_in_url = TRUE;
5548 conn->bits.user_passwd = TRUE; /* enable user+password */
5549
5550 /* Decode the user */
5551 result = Curl_urldecode(data, userp, 0, &newname, NULL, FALSE);
5552 if(result) {
5553 goto out;
5554 }
5555
5556 free(*user);
5557 *user = newname;
5558 }
5559
5560 if(passwdp) {
5561 /* We have a password in the URL so decode it */
5562 char *newpasswd;
5563 result = Curl_urldecode(data, passwdp, 0, &newpasswd, NULL, FALSE);
5564 if(result) {
5565 goto out;
5566 }
5567
5568 free(*passwd);
5569 *passwd = newpasswd;
5570 }
5571
5572 if(optionsp) {
5573 /* We have an options list in the URL so decode it */
5574 char *newoptions;
5575 result = Curl_urldecode(data, optionsp, 0, &newoptions, NULL, FALSE);
5576 if(result) {
5577 goto out;
5578 }
5579
5580 free(*options);
5581 *options = newoptions;
5582 }
5583
5584
5585 out:
5586
5587 free(userp);
5588 free(passwdp);
5589 free(optionsp);
5590
5591 return result;
5592}
5593
5594/*
5595 * parse_login_details()
5596 *
5597 * This is used to parse a login string for user name, password and options in
5598 * the following formats:
5599 *
5600 * user
5601 * user:password
5602 * user:password;options
5603 * user;options
5604 * user;options:password
5605 * :password
5606 * :password;options
5607 * ;options
5608 * ;options:password
5609 *
5610 * Parameters:
5611 *
5612 * login [in] - The login string.
5613 * len [in] - The length of the login string.
5614 * userp [in/out] - The address where a pointer to newly allocated memory
5615 * holding the user will be stored upon completion.
5616 * passdwp [in/out] - The address where a pointer to newly allocated memory
5617 * holding the password will be stored upon completion.
5618 * optionsp [in/out] - The address where a pointer to newly allocated memory
5619 * holding the options will be stored upon completion.
5620 *
5621 * Returns CURLE_OK on success.
5622 */
5623static CURLcode parse_login_details(const char *login, const size_t len,
5624 char **userp, char **passwdp,
5625 char **optionsp)
5626{
5627 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
5628 char *ubuf = NULL;
5629 char *pbuf = NULL;
5630 char *obuf = NULL;
5631 const char *psep = NULL;
5632 const char *osep = NULL;
5633 size_t ulen;
5634 size_t plen;
5635 size_t olen;
5636
5637 /* Attempt to find the password separator */
5638 if(passwdp) {
5639 psep = strchr(login, ':');
5640
5641 /* Within the constraint of the login string */
5642 if(psep >= login + len)
5643 psep = NULL;
5644 }
5645
5646 /* Attempt to find the options separator */
5647 if(optionsp) {
5648 osep = strchr(login, ';');
5649
5650 /* Within the constraint of the login string */
5651 if(osep >= login + len)
5652 osep = NULL;
5653 }
5654
5655 /* Calculate the portion lengths */
5656 ulen = (psep ?
5657 (size_t)(osep && psep > osep ? osep - login : psep - login) :
5658 (osep ? (size_t)(osep - login) : len));
5659 plen = (psep ?
5660 (osep && osep > psep ? (size_t)(osep - psep) :
5661 (size_t)(login + len - psep)) - 1 : 0);
5662 olen = (osep ?
5663 (psep && psep > osep ? (size_t)(psep - osep) :
5664 (size_t)(login + len - osep)) - 1 : 0);
5665
5666 /* Allocate the user portion buffer */
5667 if(userp && ulen) {
5668 ubuf = malloc(ulen + 1);
5669 if(!ubuf)
5670 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5671 }
5672
5673 /* Allocate the password portion buffer */
5674 if(!result && passwdp && plen) {
5675 pbuf = malloc(plen + 1);
5676 if(!pbuf) {
5677 free(ubuf);
5678 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5679 }
5680 }
5681
5682 /* Allocate the options portion buffer */
5683 if(!result && optionsp && olen) {
5684 obuf = malloc(olen + 1);
5685 if(!obuf) {
5686 free(pbuf);
5687 free(ubuf);
5688 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5689 }
5690 }
5691
5692 if(!result) {
5693 /* Store the user portion if necessary */
5694 if(ubuf) {
5695 memcpy(ubuf, login, ulen);
5696 ubuf[ulen] = '\0';
5697 Curl_safefree(*userp);
5698 *userp = ubuf;
5699 }
5700
5701 /* Store the password portion if necessary */
5702 if(pbuf) {
5703 memcpy(pbuf, psep + 1, plen);
5704 pbuf[plen] = '\0';
5705 Curl_safefree(*passwdp);
5706 *passwdp = pbuf;
5707 }
5708
5709 /* Store the options portion if necessary */
5710 if(obuf) {
5711 memcpy(obuf, osep + 1, olen);
5712 obuf[olen] = '\0';
5713 Curl_safefree(*optionsp);
5714 *optionsp = obuf;
5715 }
5716 }
5717
5718 return result;
5719}
5720
5721/*************************************************************
5722 * Figure out the remote port number and fix it in the URL
5723 *
5724 * No matter if we use a proxy or not, we have to figure out the remote
5725 * port number of various reasons.
5726 *
5727 * To be able to detect port number flawlessly, we must not confuse them
5728 * IPv6-specified addresses in the [0::1] style. (RFC2732)
5729 *
5730 * The conn->host.name is currently [user:passwd@]host[:port] where host
5731 * could be a hostname, IPv4 address or IPv6 address.
5732 *
5733 * The port number embedded in the URL is replaced, if necessary.
5734 *************************************************************/
5735static CURLcode parse_remote_port(struct Curl_easy *data,
5736 struct connectdata *conn)
5737{
5738 char *portptr;
5739 char endbracket;
5740
5741 /* Note that at this point, the IPv6 address cannot contain any scope
5742 suffix as that has already been removed in the parseurlandfillconn()
5743 function */
5744 if((1 == sscanf(conn->host.name, "[%*45[0123456789abcdefABCDEF:.]%c",
5745 &endbracket)) &&
5746 (']' == endbracket)) {
5747 /* this is a RFC2732-style specified IP-address */
5748 conn->bits.ipv6_ip = TRUE;
5749
5750 conn->host.name++; /* skip over the starting bracket */
5751 portptr = strchr(conn->host.name, ']');
5752 if(portptr) {
5753 *portptr++ = '\0'; /* zero terminate, killing the bracket */
5754 if(':' != *portptr)
5755 portptr = NULL; /* no port number available */
5756 }
5757 }
5758 else {
5759#ifdef ENABLE_IPV6
5760 struct in6_addr in6;
5761 if(Curl_inet_pton(AF_INET6, conn->host.name, &in6) > 0) {
5762 /* This is a numerical IPv6 address, meaning this is a wrongly formatted
5763 URL */
5764 failf(data, "IPv6 numerical address used in URL without brackets");
5765 return CURLE_URL_MALFORMAT;
5766 }
5767#endif
5768
5769 portptr = strchr(conn->host.name, ':');
5770 }
5771
5772 if(data->set.use_port && data->state.allow_port) {
5773 /* if set, we use this and ignore the port possibly given in the URL */
5774 conn->remote_port = (unsigned short)data->set.use_port;
5775 if(portptr)
5776 *portptr = '\0'; /* cut off the name there anyway - if there was a port
5777 number - since the port number is to be ignored! */
5778 if(conn->bits.httpproxy) {
5779 /* we need to create new URL with the new port number */
5780 char *url;
5781 char type[12]="";
5782
5783 if(conn->bits.type_set)
5784 snprintf(type, sizeof(type), ";type=%c",
5785 data->set.prefer_ascii?'A':
5786 (data->set.ftp_list_only?'D':'I'));
5787
5788 /*
5789 * This synthesized URL isn't always right--suffixes like ;type=A are
5790 * stripped off. It would be better to work directly from the original
5791 * URL and simply replace the port part of it.
5792 */
5793 url = aprintf("%s://%s%s%s:%hu%s%s%s", conn->given->scheme,
5794 conn->bits.ipv6_ip?"[":"", conn->host.name,
5795 conn->bits.ipv6_ip?"]":"", conn->remote_port,
5796 data->state.slash_removed?"/":"", data->state.path,
5797 type);
5798 if(!url)
5799 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5800
5801 if(data->change.url_alloc) {
5802 Curl_safefree(data->change.url);
5803 data->change.url_alloc = FALSE;
5804 }
5805
5806 data->change.url = url;
5807 data->change.url_alloc = TRUE;
5808 }
5809 }
5810 else if(portptr) {
5811 /* no CURLOPT_PORT given, extract the one from the URL */
5812
5813 char *rest;
5814 long port;
5815
5816 port = strtol(portptr + 1, &rest, 10); /* Port number must be decimal */
5817
5818 if((port < 0) || (port > 0xffff)) {
5819 /* Single unix standard says port numbers are 16 bits long */
5820 failf(data, "Port number out of range");
5821 return CURLE_URL_MALFORMAT;
5822 }
5823
5824 if(rest[0]) {
5825 failf(data, "Port number ended with '%c'", rest[0]);
5826 return CURLE_URL_MALFORMAT;
5827 }
5828
5829 if(rest != &portptr[1]) {
5830 *portptr = '\0'; /* cut off the name there */
5831 conn->remote_port = curlx_ultous(port);
5832 }
5833 else {
5834 /* Browser behavior adaptation. If there's a colon with no digits after,
5835 just cut off the name there which makes us ignore the colon and just
5836 use the default port. Firefox and Chrome both do that. */
5837 *portptr = '\0';
5838 }
5839 }
5840
5841 /* only if remote_port was not already parsed off the URL we use the
5842 default port number */
5843 if(conn->remote_port < 0)
5844 conn->remote_port = (unsigned short)conn->given->defport;
5845
5846 return CURLE_OK;
5847}

5849/*
5850 * Override the login details from the URL with that in the CURLOPT_USERPWD
5851 * option or a .netrc file, if applicable.
5852 */
5853static CURLcode override_login(struct Curl_easy *data,
5854 struct connectdata *conn,
5855 char **userp, char **passwdp, char **optionsp)
5856{
5857 if(data->set.str[STRING_USERNAME]) {
5858 free(*userp);
5859 *userp = strdup(data->set.str[STRING_USERNAME]);
5860 if(!*userp)
5861 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5862 }
5863
5864 if(data->set.str[STRING_PASSWORD]) {
5865 free(*passwdp);
5866 *passwdp = strdup(data->set.str[STRING_PASSWORD]);
5867 if(!*passwdp)
5868 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5869 }
5870
5871 if(data->set.str[STRING_OPTIONS]) {
5872 free(*optionsp);
5873 *optionsp = strdup(data->set.str[STRING_OPTIONS]);
5874 if(!*optionsp)
5875 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5876 }
5877
5878 conn->bits.netrc = FALSE;
5879 if(data->set.use_netrc != CURL_NETRC_IGNORED) {
5880 int ret = Curl_parsenetrc(conn->host.name,
5881 userp, passwdp,
5882 data->set.str[STRING_NETRC_FILE]);
5883 if(ret > 0) {
5884 infof(data, "Couldn't find host %s in the "
5885 DOT_CHAR "netrc file; using defaults\n",
5886 conn->host.name);
5887 }
5888 else if(ret < 0) {
5889 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5890 }
5891 else {
5892 /* set bits.netrc TRUE to remember that we got the name from a .netrc
5893 file, so that it is safe to use even if we followed a Location: to a
5894 different host or similar. */
5895 conn->bits.netrc = TRUE;
5896
5897 conn->bits.user_passwd = TRUE; /* enable user+password */
5898 }
5899 }
5900
5901 return CURLE_OK;
5902}

5904/*
5905 * Set the login details so they're available in the connection
5906 */
5907static CURLcode set_login(struct connectdata *conn,
5908 const char *user, const char *passwd,
5909 const char *options)
5910{
5911 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
5912
5913 /* If our protocol needs a password and we have none, use the defaults */
5914 if((conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_NEEDSPWD) && !conn->bits.user_passwd) {
5915 /* Store the default user */
5916 conn->user = strdup(CURL_DEFAULT_USER);
5917
5918 /* Store the default password */
5919 if(conn->user)
5920 conn->passwd = strdup(CURL_DEFAULT_PASSWORD);
5921 else
5922 conn->passwd = NULL;
5923
5924 /* This is the default password, so DON'T set conn->bits.user_passwd */
5925 }
5926 else {
5927 /* Store the user, zero-length if not set */
5928 conn->user = strdup(user);
5929
5930 /* Store the password (only if user is present), zero-length if not set */
5931 if(conn->user)
5932 conn->passwd = strdup(passwd);
5933 else
5934 conn->passwd = NULL;
5935 }
5936
5937 if(!conn->user || !conn->passwd)
5938 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5939
5940 /* Store the options, null if not set */
5941 if(!result && options[0]) {
5942 conn->options = strdup(options);
5943
5944 if(!conn->options)
5945 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5946 }
5947
5948 return result;
5949}

5951/*
5952 * Parses a "host:port" string to connect to.
5953 * The hostname and the port may be empty; in this case, NULL is returned for
5954 * the hostname and -1 for the port.
5955 */
5956static CURLcode parse_connect_to_host_port(struct Curl_easy *data,
5957 const char *host,
5958 char **hostname_result,
5959 int *port_result)
5960{
5961 char *host_dup;
5962 char *hostptr;
5963 char *host_portno;
5964 char *portptr;
5965 int port = -1;
5966
5967#if defined(CURL_DISABLE_VERBOSE_STRINGS)
5968 (void) data;
5969#endif
5970
5971 *hostname_result = NULL;
5972 *port_result = -1;
5973
5974 if(!host || !*host)
5975 return CURLE_OK;
5976
5977 host_dup = strdup(host);
5978 if(!host_dup)
5979 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
5980
5981 hostptr = host_dup;
5982
5983 /* start scanning for port number at this point */
5984 portptr = hostptr;
5985
5986 /* detect and extract RFC6874-style IPv6-addresses */
5987 if(*hostptr == '[') {
5988 char *ptr = ++hostptr; /* advance beyond the initial bracket */
5989 while(*ptr && (ISXDIGIT(*ptr) || (*ptr == ':') || (*ptr == '.')))
5990 ptr++;
5991 if(*ptr == '%') {
5992 /* There might be a zone identifier */
5993 if(strncmp("%25", ptr, 3))
5994 infof(data, "Please URL encode %% as %%25, see RFC 6874.\n");
5995 ptr++;
5996 /* Allow unreserved characters as defined in RFC 3986 */
5997 while(*ptr && (ISALPHA(*ptr) || ISXDIGIT(*ptr) || (*ptr == '-') ||
5998 (*ptr == '.') || (*ptr == '_') || (*ptr == '~')))
5999 ptr++;
6000 }
6001 if(*ptr == ']')
6002 /* yeps, it ended nicely with a bracket as well */
6003 *ptr++ = '\0';
6004 else
6005 infof(data, "Invalid IPv6 address format\n");
6006 portptr = ptr;
6007 /* Note that if this didn't end with a bracket, we still advanced the
6008 * hostptr first, but I can't see anything wrong with that as no host
6009 * name nor a numeric can legally start with a bracket.
6010 */
6011 }
6012
6013 /* Get port number off server.com:1080 */
6014 host_portno = strchr(portptr, ':');
6015 if(host_portno) {
6016 char *endp = NULL;
6017 *host_portno = '\0'; /* cut off number from host name */
6018 host_portno++;
6019 if(*host_portno) {
6020 long portparse = strtol(host_portno, &endp, 10);
6021 if((endp && *endp) || (portparse < 0) || (portparse > 65535)) {
6022 infof(data, "No valid port number in connect to host string (%s)\n",
6023 host_portno);
6024 hostptr = NULL;
6025 port = -1;
6026 }
6027 else
6028 port = (int)portparse; /* we know it will fit */
6029 }
6030 }
6031
6032 /* now, clone the cleaned host name */
6033 if(hostptr) {
6034 *hostname_result = strdup(hostptr);
6035 if(!*hostname_result) {
6036 free(host_dup);
6037 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6038 }
6039 }
6040
6041 *port_result = port;
6042
6043 free(host_dup);
6044 return CURLE_OK;
6045}
6046
6047/*
6048 * Parses one "connect to" string in the form:
6049 * "HOST:PORT:CONNECT-TO-HOST:CONNECT-TO-PORT".
6050 */
6051static CURLcode parse_connect_to_string(struct Curl_easy *data,
6052 struct connectdata *conn,
6053 const char *conn_to_host,
6054 char **host_result,
6055 int *port_result)
6056{
6057 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
6058 const char *ptr = conn_to_host;
6059 int host_match = FALSE;
6060 int port_match = FALSE;
6061
6062 *host_result = NULL;
6063 *port_result = -1;
6064
6065 if(*ptr == ':') {
6066 /* an empty hostname always matches */
6067 host_match = TRUE;
6068 ptr++;
6069 }
6070 else {
6071 /* check whether the URL's hostname matches */
6072 size_t hostname_to_match_len;
6073 char *hostname_to_match = aprintf("%s%s%s",
6074 conn->bits.ipv6_ip ? "[" : "",
6075 conn->host.name,
6076 conn->bits.ipv6_ip ? "]" : "");
6077 if(!hostname_to_match)
6078 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6079 hostname_to_match_len = strlen(hostname_to_match);
6080 host_match = strncasecompare(ptr, hostname_to_match,
6081 hostname_to_match_len);
6082 free(hostname_to_match);
6083 ptr += hostname_to_match_len;
6084
6085 host_match = host_match && *ptr == ':';
6086 ptr++;
6087 }
6088
6089 if(host_match) {
6090 if(*ptr == ':') {
6091 /* an empty port always matches */
6092 port_match = TRUE;
6093 ptr++;
6094 }
6095 else {
6096 /* check whether the URL's port matches */
6097 char *ptr_next = strchr(ptr, ':');
6098 if(ptr_next) {
6099 char *endp = NULL;
6100 long port_to_match = strtol(ptr, &endp, 10);
6101 if((endp == ptr_next) && (port_to_match == conn->remote_port)) {
6102 port_match = TRUE;
6103 ptr = ptr_next + 1;
6104 }
6105 }
6106 }
6107 }
6108
6109 if(host_match && port_match) {
6110 /* parse the hostname and port to connect to */
6111 result = parse_connect_to_host_port(data, ptr, host_result, port_result);
6112 }
6113
6114 return result;
6115}

6117/*
6118 * Processes all strings in the "connect to" slist, and uses the "connect
6119 * to host" and "connect to port" of the first string that matches.
6120 */
6121static CURLcode parse_connect_to_slist(struct Curl_easy *data,
6122 struct connectdata *conn,
6123 struct curl_slist *conn_to_host)
6124{
6125 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
6126 char *host = NULL;
6127 int port = -1;
6128
6129 while(conn_to_host && !host && port == -1) {
6130 result = parse_connect_to_string(data, conn, conn_to_host->data,
6131 &host, &port);
6132 if(result)
6133 return result;
6134
6135 if(host && *host) {
6136 conn->conn_to_host.rawalloc = host;
6137 conn->conn_to_host.name = host;
6138 conn->bits.conn_to_host = TRUE;
6139
6140 infof(data, "Connecting to hostname: %s\n", host);
6141 }
6142 else {
6143 /* no "connect to host" */
6144 conn->bits.conn_to_host = FALSE;
6145 Curl_safefree(host);
6146 }
6147
6148 if(port >= 0) {
6149 conn->conn_to_port = port;
6150 conn->bits.conn_to_port = TRUE;
6151 infof(data, "Connecting to port: %d\n", port);
6152 }
6153 else {
6154 /* no "connect to port" */
6155 conn->bits.conn_to_port = FALSE;
6156 port = -1;
6157 }
6158
6159 conn_to_host = conn_to_host->next;
6160 }
6161
6162 return result;
6163}

6165/*************************************************************
6166 * Resolve the address of the server or proxy
6167 *************************************************************/
6168static CURLcode resolve_server(struct Curl_easy *data,
6169 struct connectdata *conn,
6170 bool *async)
6171{
6172 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
6173 time_t timeout_ms = Curl_timeleft(data, NULL, TRUE);
6174
6175 /*************************************************************
6176 * Resolve the name of the server or proxy
6177 *************************************************************/
6178 if(conn->bits.reuse)
6179 /* We're reusing the connection - no need to resolve anything, and
6180 fix_hostname() was called already in create_conn() for the re-use
6181 case. */
6182 *async = FALSE;
6183
6184 else {
6185 /* this is a fresh connect */
6186 int rc;
6187 struct Curl_dns_entry *hostaddr;
6188
6189#ifdef USE_UNIX_SOCKETS
6190 if(conn->unix_domain_socket) {
6191 /* Unix domain sockets are local. The host gets ignored, just use the
6192 * specified domain socket address. Do not cache "DNS entries". There is
6193 * no DNS involved and we already have the filesystem path available */
6194 const char *path = conn->unix_domain_socket;
6195
6196 hostaddr = calloc(1, sizeof(struct Curl_dns_entry));
6197 if(!hostaddr)
6198 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6199 else {
6200 bool longpath = FALSE;
6201 hostaddr->addr = Curl_unix2addr(path, &longpath,
6202 conn->abstract_unix_socket);
6203 if(hostaddr->addr)
6204 hostaddr->inuse++;
6205 else {
6206 /* Long paths are not supported for now */
6207 if(longpath) {
6208 failf(data, "Unix socket path too long: '%s'", path);
6209 result = CURLE_COULDNT_RESOLVE_HOST;
6210 }
6211 else
6212 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6213 free(hostaddr);
6214 hostaddr = NULL;
6215 }
6216 }
6217 }
6218 else
6219#endif
6220 if(!conn->bits.proxy) {
6221 struct hostname *connhost;
6222 if(conn->bits.conn_to_host)
6223 connhost = &conn->conn_to_host;
6224 else
6225 connhost = &conn->host;
6226
6227 /* If not connecting via a proxy, extract the port from the URL, if it is
6228 * there, thus overriding any defaults that might have been set above. */
6229 if(conn->bits.conn_to_port)
6230 conn->port = conn->conn_to_port;
6231 else
6232 conn->port = conn->remote_port;
6233
6234 /* Resolve target host right on */
6235 rc = Curl_resolv_timeout(conn, connhost->name, (int)conn->port,
6236 &hostaddr, timeout_ms);
6237 if(rc == CURLRESOLV_PENDING)
6238 *async = TRUE;
6239
6240 else if(rc == CURLRESOLV_TIMEDOUT)
6241 result = CURLE_OPERATION_TIMEDOUT;
6242
6243 else if(!hostaddr) {
6244 failf(data, "Couldn't resolve host '%s'", connhost->dispname);
6245 result = CURLE_COULDNT_RESOLVE_HOST;
6246 /* don't return yet, we need to clean up the timeout first */
6247 }
6248 }
6249 else {
6250 /* This is a proxy that hasn't been resolved yet. */
6251
6252 struct hostname * const host = conn->bits.socksproxy ?
6253 &conn->socks_proxy.host : &conn->http_proxy.host;
6254
6255 /* resolve proxy */
6256 rc = Curl_resolv_timeout(conn, host->name, (int)conn->port,
6257 &hostaddr, timeout_ms);
6258
6259 if(rc == CURLRESOLV_PENDING)
6260 *async = TRUE;
6261
6262 else if(rc == CURLRESOLV_TIMEDOUT)
6263 result = CURLE_OPERATION_TIMEDOUT;
6264
6265 else if(!hostaddr) {
6266 failf(data, "Couldn't resolve proxy '%s'", host->dispname);
6267 result = CURLE_COULDNT_RESOLVE_PROXY;
6268 /* don't return yet, we need to clean up the timeout first */
6269 }
6270 }
6271 DEBUGASSERT(conn->dns_entry == NULL);
6272 conn->dns_entry = hostaddr;
6273 }
6274
6275 return result;
6276}

6278/*
6279 * Cleanup the connection just allocated before we can move along and use the
6280 * previously existing one. All relevant data is copied over and old_conn is
6281 * ready for freeing once this function returns.
6282 */
6283static void reuse_conn(struct connectdata *old_conn,
6284 struct connectdata *conn)
6285{
6286 free_fixed_hostname(&old_conn->http_proxy.host);
6287 free_fixed_hostname(&old_conn->socks_proxy.host);
6288
6289 free(old_conn->http_proxy.host.rawalloc);
6290 free(old_conn->socks_proxy.host.rawalloc);
6291
6292 /* free the SSL config struct from this connection struct as this was
6293 allocated in vain and is targeted for destruction */
6294 Curl_free_primary_ssl_config(&old_conn->ssl_config);
6295 Curl_free_primary_ssl_config(&old_conn->proxy_ssl_config);
6296
6297 conn->data = old_conn->data;
6298
6299 /* get the user+password information from the old_conn struct since it may
6300 * be new for this request even when we re-use an existing connection */
6301 conn->bits.user_passwd = old_conn->bits.user_passwd;
6302 if(conn->bits.user_passwd) {
6303 /* use the new user name and password though */
6304 Curl_safefree(conn->user);
6305 Curl_safefree(conn->passwd);
6306 conn->user = old_conn->user;
6307 conn->passwd = old_conn->passwd;
6308 old_conn->user = NULL;
6309 old_conn->passwd = NULL;
6310 }
6311
6312 conn->bits.proxy_user_passwd = old_conn->bits.proxy_user_passwd;
6313 if(conn->bits.proxy_user_passwd) {
6314 /* use the new proxy user name and proxy password though */
6315 Curl_safefree(conn->http_proxy.user);
6316 Curl_safefree(conn->socks_proxy.user);
6317 Curl_safefree(conn->http_proxy.passwd);
6318 Curl_safefree(conn->socks_proxy.passwd);
6319 conn->http_proxy.user = old_conn->http_proxy.user;
6320 conn->socks_proxy.user = old_conn->socks_proxy.user;
6321 conn->http_proxy.passwd = old_conn->http_proxy.passwd;
6322 conn->socks_proxy.passwd = old_conn->socks_proxy.passwd;
6323 old_conn->http_proxy.user = NULL;
6324 old_conn->socks_proxy.user = NULL;
6325 old_conn->http_proxy.passwd = NULL;
6326 old_conn->socks_proxy.passwd = NULL;
6327 }
6328
6329 /* host can change, when doing keepalive with a proxy or if the case is
6330 different this time etc */
6331 free_fixed_hostname(&conn->host);
6332 free_fixed_hostname(&conn->conn_to_host);
6333 Curl_safefree(conn->host.rawalloc);
6334 Curl_safefree(conn->conn_to_host.rawalloc);
6335 conn->host = old_conn->host;
6336 conn->conn_to_host = old_conn->conn_to_host;
6337 conn->conn_to_port = old_conn->conn_to_port;
6338 conn->remote_port = old_conn->remote_port;
6339
6340 /* persist connection info in session handle */
6341 Curl_persistconninfo(conn);
6342
6343 conn_reset_all_postponed_data(old_conn); /* free buffers */
6344
6345 /* re-use init */
6346 conn->bits.reuse = TRUE; /* yes, we're re-using here */
6347
6348 Curl_safefree(old_conn->user);
6349 Curl_safefree(old_conn->passwd);
6350 Curl_safefree(old_conn->http_proxy.user);
6351 Curl_safefree(old_conn->socks_proxy.user);
6352 Curl_safefree(old_conn->http_proxy.passwd);
6353 Curl_safefree(old_conn->socks_proxy.passwd);
6354 Curl_safefree(old_conn->localdev);
6355
6356 Curl_llist_destroy(&old_conn->send_pipe, NULL);
6357 Curl_llist_destroy(&old_conn->recv_pipe, NULL);
6358
6359 Curl_safefree(old_conn->master_buffer);
6360
6361#ifdef USE_UNIX_SOCKETS
6362 Curl_safefree(old_conn->unix_domain_socket);
6363#endif
6364}

6366/**
6367 * create_conn() sets up a new connectdata struct, or re-uses an already
6368 * existing one, and resolves host name.
6369 *
6370 * if this function returns CURLE_OK and *async is set to TRUE, the resolve
6371 * response will be coming asynchronously. If *async is FALSE, the name is
6372 * already resolved.
6373 *
6374 * @param data The sessionhandle pointer
6375 * @param in_connect is set to the next connection data pointer
6376 * @param async is set TRUE when an async DNS resolution is pending
6377 * @see Curl_setup_conn()
6378 *
6379 * *NOTE* this function assigns the conn->data pointer!
6380 */
6381
6382static CURLcode create_conn(struct Curl_easy *data,
6383 struct connectdata **in_connect,
6384 bool *async)
6385{
6386 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
6387 struct connectdata *conn;
6388 struct connectdata *conn_temp = NULL;
6389 size_t urllen;
6390 char *user = NULL;
6391 char *passwd = NULL;
6392 char *options = NULL;
6393 bool reuse;
6394 bool prot_missing = FALSE;
6395 bool connections_available = TRUE;
6396 bool force_reuse = FALSE;
6397 bool waitpipe = FALSE;
6398 size_t max_host_connections = Curl_multi_max_host_connections(data->multi);
6399 size_t max_total_connections = Curl_multi_max_total_connections(data->multi);
6400
6401 *async = FALSE;
6402
6403 /*************************************************************
6404 * Check input data
6405 *************************************************************/
6406
6407 if(!data->change.url) {
6408 result = CURLE_URL_MALFORMAT;
6409 goto out;
6410 }
6411
6412 /* First, split up the current URL in parts so that we can use the
6413 parts for checking against the already present connections. In order
6414 to not have to modify everything at once, we allocate a temporary
6415 connection data struct and fill in for comparison purposes. */
6416 conn = allocate_conn(data);
6417
6418 if(!conn) {
6419 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6420 goto out;
6421 }
6422
6423 /* We must set the return variable as soon as possible, so that our
6424 parent can cleanup any possible allocs we may have done before
6425 any failure */
6426 *in_connect = conn;
6427
6428 /* This initing continues below, see the comment "Continue connectdata
6429 * initialization here" */
6430
6431 /***********************************************************
6432 * We need to allocate memory to store the path in. We get the size of the
6433 * full URL to be sure, and we need to make it at least 256 bytes since
6434 * other parts of the code will rely on this fact
6435 ***********************************************************/
6436#define LEAST_PATH_ALLOC 256
6437 urllen = strlen(data->change.url);
6438 if(urllen < LEAST_PATH_ALLOC)
6439 urllen = LEAST_PATH_ALLOC;
6440
6441 /*
6442 * We malloc() the buffers below urllen+2 to make room for 2 possibilities:
6443 * 1 - an extra terminating zero
6444 * 2 - an extra slash (in case a syntax like "www.host.com?moo" is used)
6445 */
6446
6447 Curl_safefree(data->state.pathbuffer);
6448 data->state.path = NULL;
6449
6450 data->state.pathbuffer = malloc(urllen + 2);
6451 if(NULL == data->state.pathbuffer) {
6452 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY; /* really bad error */
6453 goto out;
6454 }
6455 data->state.path = data->state.pathbuffer;
6456
6457 conn->host.rawalloc = malloc(urllen + 2);
6458 if(NULL == conn->host.rawalloc) {
6459 Curl_safefree(data->state.pathbuffer);
6460 data->state.path = NULL;
6461 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6462 goto out;
6463 }
6464
6465 conn->host.name = conn->host.rawalloc;
6466 conn->host.name[0] = 0;
6467
6468 user = strdup("");
6469 passwd = strdup("");
6470 options = strdup("");
6471 if(!user || !passwd || !options) {
6472 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6473 goto out;
6474 }
6475
6476 result = parseurlandfillconn(data, conn, &prot_missing, &user, &passwd,
6477 &options);
6478 if(result)
6479 goto out;
6480
6481 /*************************************************************
6482 * No protocol part in URL was used, add it!
6483 *************************************************************/
6484 if(prot_missing) {
6485 /* We're guessing prefixes here and if we're told to use a proxy or if
6486 we're gonna follow a Location: later or... then we need the protocol
6487 part added so that we have a valid URL. */
6488 char *reurl;
6489 char *ch_lower;
6490
6491 reurl = aprintf("%s://%s", conn->handler->scheme, data->change.url);
6492
6493 if(!reurl) {
6494 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6495 goto out;
6496 }
6497
6498 /* Change protocol prefix to lower-case */
6499 for(ch_lower = reurl; *ch_lower != ':'; ch_lower++)
6500 *ch_lower = (char)TOLOWER(*ch_lower);
6501
6502 if(data->change.url_alloc) {
6503 Curl_safefree(data->change.url);
6504 data->change.url_alloc = FALSE;
6505 }
6506
6507 data->change.url = reurl;
6508 data->change.url_alloc = TRUE; /* free this later */
6509 }
6510
6511 /*************************************************************
6512 * If the protocol can't handle url query strings, then cut
6513 * off the unhandable part
6514 *************************************************************/
6515 if((conn->given->flags&PROTOPT_NOURLQUERY)) {
6516 char *path_q_sep = strchr(conn->data->state.path, '?');
6517 if(path_q_sep) {
6518 /* according to rfc3986, allow the query (?foo=bar)
6519 also on protocols that can't handle it.
6520
6521 cut the string-part after '?'
6522 */
6523
6524 /* terminate the string */
6525 path_q_sep[0] = 0;
6526 }
6527 }
6528
6529 if(data->set.str[STRING_BEARER]) {
6530 conn->oauth_bearer = strdup(data->set.str[STRING_BEARER]);
6531 if(!conn->oauth_bearer) {
6532 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6533 goto out;
6534 }
6535 }
6536
6537#ifdef USE_UNIX_SOCKETS
6538 if(data->set.str[STRING_UNIX_SOCKET_PATH]) {
6539 conn->unix_domain_socket = strdup(data->set.str[STRING_UNIX_SOCKET_PATH]);
6540 if(conn->unix_domain_socket == NULL) {
6541 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6542 goto out;
6543 }
6544 conn->abstract_unix_socket = data->set.abstract_unix_socket;
6545 }
6546#endif
6547
6548 /* After the unix socket init but before the proxy vars are used, parse and
6549 initialize the proxy vars */
6550#ifndef CURL_DISABLE_PROXY
6551 result = create_conn_helper_init_proxy(conn);
6552 if(result)
6553 goto out;
6554#endif
6555
6556 /*************************************************************
6557 * If the protocol is using SSL and HTTP proxy is used, we set
6558 * the tunnel_proxy bit.
6559 *************************************************************/
6560 if((conn->given->flags&PROTOPT_SSL) && conn->bits.httpproxy)
6561 conn->bits.tunnel_proxy = TRUE;
6562
6563 /*************************************************************
6564 * Figure out the remote port number and fix it in the URL
6565 *************************************************************/
6566 result = parse_remote_port(data, conn);
6567 if(result)
6568 goto out;
6569
6570 /* Check for overridden login details and set them accordingly so they
6571 they are known when protocol->setup_connection is called! */
6572 result = override_login(data, conn, &user, &passwd, &options);
6573 if(result)
6574 goto out;
6575 result = set_login(conn, user, passwd, options);
6576 if(result)
6577 goto out;
6578
6579 /*************************************************************
6580 * Process the "connect to" linked list of hostname/port mappings.
6581 * Do this after the remote port number has been fixed in the URL.
6582 *************************************************************/
6583 result = parse_connect_to_slist(data, conn, data->set.connect_to);
6584 if(result)
6585 goto out;
6586
6587 /*************************************************************
6588 * IDN-fix the hostnames
6589 *************************************************************/
6590 fix_hostname(conn, &conn->host);
6591 if(conn->bits.conn_to_host)
6592 fix_hostname(conn, &conn->conn_to_host);
6593 if(conn->bits.httpproxy)
6594 fix_hostname(conn, &conn->http_proxy.host);
6595 if(conn->bits.socksproxy)
6596 fix_hostname(conn, &conn->socks_proxy.host);
6597
6598 /*************************************************************
6599 * Check whether the host and the "connect to host" are equal.
6600 * Do this after the hostnames have been IDN-fixed.
6601 *************************************************************/
6602 if(conn->bits.conn_to_host &&
6603 strcasecompare(conn->conn_to_host.name, conn->host.name)) {
6604 conn->bits.conn_to_host = FALSE;
6605 }
6606
6607 /*************************************************************
6608 * Check whether the port and the "connect to port" are equal.
6609 * Do this after the remote port number has been fixed in the URL.
6610 *************************************************************/
6611 if(conn->bits.conn_to_port && conn->conn_to_port == conn->remote_port) {
6612 conn->bits.conn_to_port = FALSE;
6613 }
6614
6615 /*************************************************************
6616 * If the "connect to" feature is used with an HTTP proxy,
6617 * we set the tunnel_proxy bit.
6618 *************************************************************/
6619 if((conn->bits.conn_to_host || conn->bits.conn_to_port) &&
6620 conn->bits.httpproxy)
6621 conn->bits.tunnel_proxy = TRUE;
6622
6623 /*************************************************************
6624 * Setup internals depending on protocol. Needs to be done after
6625 * we figured out what/if proxy to use.
6626 *************************************************************/
6627 result = setup_connection_internals(conn);
6628 if(result)
6629 goto out;
6630
6631 conn->recv[FIRSTSOCKET] = Curl_recv_plain;
6632 conn->send[FIRSTSOCKET] = Curl_send_plain;
6633 conn->recv[SECONDARYSOCKET] = Curl_recv_plain;
6634 conn->send[SECONDARYSOCKET] = Curl_send_plain;
6635
6636 conn->bits.tcp_fastopen = data->set.tcp_fastopen;
6637
6638 /***********************************************************************
6639 * file: is a special case in that it doesn't need a network connection
6640 ***********************************************************************/
6641#ifndef CURL_DISABLE_FILE
6642 if(conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_NONETWORK) {
6643 bool done;
6644 /* this is supposed to be the connect function so we better at least check
6645 that the file is present here! */
6646 DEBUGASSERT(conn->handler->connect_it);
6647 result = conn->handler->connect_it(conn, &done);
6648
6649 /* Setup a "faked" transfer that'll do nothing */
6650 if(!result) {
6651 conn->data = data;
6652 conn->bits.tcpconnect[FIRSTSOCKET] = TRUE; /* we are "connected */
6653
6654 Curl_conncache_add_conn(data->state.conn_cache, conn);
6655
6656 /*
6657 * Setup whatever necessary for a resumed transfer
6658 */
6659 result = setup_range(data);
6660 if(result) {
6661 DEBUGASSERT(conn->handler->done);
6662 /* we ignore the return code for the protocol-specific DONE */
6663 (void)conn->handler->done(conn, result, FALSE);
6664 goto out;
6665 }
6666
6667 Curl_setup_transfer(conn, -1, -1, FALSE, NULL, /* no download */
6668 -1, NULL); /* no upload */
6669 }
6670
6671 /* since we skip do_init() */
6672 Curl_init_do(data, conn);
6673
6674 goto out;
6675 }
6676#endif
6677
6678 /* Get a cloned copy of the SSL config situation stored in the
6679 connection struct. But to get this going nicely, we must first make
6680 sure that the strings in the master copy are pointing to the correct
6681 strings in the session handle strings array!
6682
6683 Keep in mind that the pointers in the master copy are pointing to strings
6684 that will be freed as part of the Curl_easy struct, but all cloned
6685 copies will be separately allocated.
6686 */
6687 data->set.ssl.primary.CApath = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CAPATH_ORIG];
6688 data->set.proxy_ssl.primary.CApath = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CAPATH_PROXY];
6689 data->set.ssl.primary.CAfile = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CAFILE_ORIG];
6690 data->set.proxy_ssl.primary.CAfile = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CAFILE_PROXY];
6691 data->set.ssl.primary.random_file = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_RANDOM_FILE];
6692 data->set.proxy_ssl.primary.random_file =
6693 data->set.str[STRING_SSL_RANDOM_FILE];
6694 data->set.ssl.primary.egdsocket = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_EGDSOCKET];
6695 data->set.proxy_ssl.primary.egdsocket = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_EGDSOCKET];
6696 data->set.ssl.primary.cipher_list =
6697 data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CIPHER_LIST_ORIG];
6698 data->set.proxy_ssl.primary.cipher_list =
6699 data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CIPHER_LIST_PROXY];
6700
6701 data->set.ssl.CRLfile = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CRLFILE_ORIG];
6702 data->set.proxy_ssl.CRLfile = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_CRLFILE_PROXY];
6703 data->set.ssl.issuercert = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_ISSUERCERT_ORIG];
6704 data->set.proxy_ssl.issuercert = data->set.str[STRING_SSL_ISSUERCERT_PROXY];
6705 data->set.ssl.cert = data->set.str[STRING_CERT_ORIG];
6706 data->set.proxy_ssl.cert = data->set.str[STRING_CERT_PROXY];
6707 data->set.ssl.cert_type = data->set.str[STRING_CERT_TYPE_ORIG];
6708 data->set.proxy_ssl.cert_type = data->set.str[STRING_CERT_TYPE_PROXY];
6709 data->set.ssl.key = data->set.str[STRING_KEY_ORIG];
6710 data->set.proxy_ssl.key = data->set.str[STRING_KEY_PROXY];
6711 data->set.ssl.key_type = data->set.str[STRING_KEY_TYPE_ORIG];
6712 data->set.proxy_ssl.key_type = data->set.str[STRING_KEY_TYPE_PROXY];
6713 data->set.ssl.key_passwd = data->set.str[STRING_KEY_PASSWD_ORIG];
6714 data->set.proxy_ssl.key_passwd = data->set.str[STRING_KEY_PASSWD_PROXY];
6715 data->set.ssl.primary.clientcert = data->set.str[STRING_CERT_ORIG];
6716 data->set.proxy_ssl.primary.clientcert = data->set.str[STRING_CERT_PROXY];
6717#ifdef USE_TLS_SRP
6718 data->set.ssl.username = data->set.str[STRING_TLSAUTH_USERNAME_ORIG];
6719 data->set.proxy_ssl.username = data->set.str[STRING_TLSAUTH_USERNAME_PROXY];
6720 data->set.ssl.password = data->set.str[STRING_TLSAUTH_PASSWORD_ORIG];
6721 data->set.proxy_ssl.password = data->set.str[STRING_TLSAUTH_PASSWORD_PROXY];
6722#endif
6723
6724 if(!Curl_clone_primary_ssl_config(&data->set.ssl.primary,
6725 &conn->ssl_config)) {
6726 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6727 goto out;
6728 }
6729
6730 if(!Curl_clone_primary_ssl_config(&data->set.proxy_ssl.primary,
6731 &conn->proxy_ssl_config)) {
6732 result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6733 goto out;
6734 }
6735
6736 prune_dead_connections(data);
6737
6738 /*************************************************************
6739 * Check the current list of connections to see if we can
6740 * re-use an already existing one or if we have to create a
6741 * new one.
6742 *************************************************************/
6743
6744 /* reuse_fresh is TRUE if we are told to use a new connection by force, but
6745 we only acknowledge this option if this is not a re-used connection
6746 already (which happens due to follow-location or during a HTTP
6747 authentication phase). */
6748 if(data->set.reuse_fresh && !data->state.this_is_a_follow)
6749 reuse = FALSE;
6750 else
6751 reuse = ConnectionExists(data, conn, &conn_temp, &force_reuse, &waitpipe);
6752
6753 /* If we found a reusable connection, we may still want to
6754 open a new connection if we are pipelining. */
6755 if(reuse && !force_reuse && IsPipeliningPossible(data, conn_temp)) {
6756 size_t pipelen = conn_temp->send_pipe.size + conn_temp->recv_pipe.size;
6757 if(pipelen > 0) {
6758 infof(data, "Found connection %ld, with requests in the pipe (%zu)\n",
6759 conn_temp->connection_id, pipelen);
6760
6761 if(conn_temp->bundle->num_connections < max_host_connections &&
6762 data->state.conn_cache->num_connections < max_total_connections) {
6763 /* We want a new connection anyway */
6764 reuse = FALSE;
6765
6766 infof(data, "We can reuse, but we want a new connection anyway\n");
6767 }
6768 }
6769 }
6770
6771 if(reuse) {
6772 /*
6773 * We already have a connection for this, we got the former connection
6774 * in the conn_temp variable and thus we need to cleanup the one we
6775 * just allocated before we can move along and use the previously
6776 * existing one.
6777 */
6778 conn_temp->inuse = TRUE; /* mark this as being in use so that no other
6779 handle in a multi stack may nick it */
6780 reuse_conn(conn, conn_temp);
6781 free(conn); /* we don't need this anymore */
6782 conn = conn_temp;
6783 *in_connect = conn;
6784
6785 infof(data, "Re-using existing connection! (#%ld) with %s %s\n",
6786 conn->connection_id,
6787 conn->bits.proxy?"proxy":"host",
6788 conn->socks_proxy.host.name ? conn->socks_proxy.host.dispname :
6789 conn->http_proxy.host.name ? conn->http_proxy.host.dispname :
6790 conn->host.dispname);
6791 }
6792 else {
6793 /* We have decided that we want a new connection. However, we may not
6794 be able to do that if we have reached the limit of how many
6795 connections we are allowed to open. */
6796 struct connectbundle *bundle = NULL;
6797
6798 if(conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_ALPN_NPN) {
6799 /* The protocol wants it, so set the bits if enabled in the easy handle
6800 (default) */
6801 if(data->set.ssl_enable_alpn)
6802 conn->bits.tls_enable_alpn = TRUE;
6803 if(data->set.ssl_enable_npn)
6804 conn->bits.tls_enable_npn = TRUE;
6805 }
6806
6807 if(waitpipe)
6808 /* There is a connection that *might* become usable for pipelining
6809 "soon", and we wait for that */
6810 connections_available = FALSE;
6811 else
6812 bundle = Curl_conncache_find_bundle(conn, data->state.conn_cache);
6813
6814 if(max_host_connections > 0 && bundle &&
6815 (bundle->num_connections >= max_host_connections)) {
6816 struct connectdata *conn_candidate;
6817
6818 /* The bundle is full. Let's see if we can kill a connection. */
6819 conn_candidate = find_oldest_idle_connection_in_bundle(data, bundle);
6820
6821 if(conn_candidate) {
6822 /* Set the connection's owner correctly, then kill it */
6823 conn_candidate->data = data;
6824 (void)Curl_disconnect(conn_candidate, /* dead_connection */ FALSE);
6825 }
6826 else {
6827 infof(data, "No more connections allowed to host: %d\n",
6828 max_host_connections);
6829 connections_available = FALSE;
6830 }
6831 }
6832
6833 if(connections_available &&
6834 (max_total_connections > 0) &&
6835 (data->state.conn_cache->num_connections >= max_total_connections)) {
6836 struct connectdata *conn_candidate;
6837
6838 /* The cache is full. Let's see if we can kill a connection. */
6839 conn_candidate = Curl_oldest_idle_connection(data);
6840
6841 if(conn_candidate) {
6842 /* Set the connection's owner correctly, then kill it */
6843 conn_candidate->data = data;
6844 (void)Curl_disconnect(conn_candidate, /* dead_connection */ FALSE);
6845 }
6846 else {
6847 infof(data, "No connections available in cache\n");
6848 connections_available = FALSE;
6849 }
6850 }
6851
6852 if(!connections_available) {
6853 infof(data, "No connections available.\n");
6854
6855 conn_free(conn);
6856 *in_connect = NULL;
6857
6858 result = CURLE_NO_CONNECTION_AVAILABLE;
6859 goto out;
6860 }
6861 else {
6862 /*
6863 * This is a brand new connection, so let's store it in the connection
6864 * cache of ours!
6865 */
6866 Curl_conncache_add_conn(data->state.conn_cache, conn);
6867 }
6868
6869#if defined(USE_NTLM)
6870 /* If NTLM is requested in a part of this connection, make sure we don't
6871 assume the state is fine as this is a fresh connection and NTLM is
6872 connection based. */
6873 if((data->state.authhost.picked & (CURLAUTH_NTLM | CURLAUTH_NTLM_WB)) &&
6874 data->state.authhost.done) {
6875 infof(data, "NTLM picked AND auth done set, clear picked!\n");
6876 data->state.authhost.picked = CURLAUTH_NONE;
6877 data->state.authhost.done = FALSE;
6878 }
6879
6880 if((data->state.authproxy.picked & (CURLAUTH_NTLM | CURLAUTH_NTLM_WB)) &&
6881 data->state.authproxy.done) {
6882 infof(data, "NTLM-proxy picked AND auth done set, clear picked!\n");
6883 data->state.authproxy.picked = CURLAUTH_NONE;
6884 data->state.authproxy.done = FALSE;
6885 }
6886#endif
6887 }
6888
6889 /* Mark the connection as used */
6890 conn->inuse = TRUE;
6891
6892 /* Setup and init stuff before DO starts, in preparing for the transfer. */
6893 Curl_init_do(data, conn);
6894
6895 /*
6896 * Setup whatever necessary for a resumed transfer
6897 */
6898 result = setup_range(data);
6899 if(result)
6900 goto out;
6901
6902 /* Continue connectdata initialization here. */
6903
6904 /*
6905 * Inherit the proper values from the urldata struct AFTER we have arranged
6906 * the persistent connection stuff
6907 */
6908 conn->seek_func = data->set.seek_func;
6909 conn->seek_client = data->set.seek_client;
6910
6911 /*************************************************************
6912 * Resolve the address of the server or proxy
6913 *************************************************************/
6914 result = resolve_server(data, conn, async);
6915
6916out:
6917
6918 free(options);
6919 free(passwd);
6920 free(user);
6921 return result;
6922}
6923
6924/* Curl_setup_conn() is called after the name resolve initiated in
6925 * create_conn() is all done.
6926 *
6927 * Curl_setup_conn() also handles reused connections
6928 *
6929 * conn->data MUST already have been setup fine (in create_conn)
6930 */
6931
6932CURLcode Curl_setup_conn(struct connectdata *conn,
6933 bool *protocol_done)
6934{
6935 CURLcode result = CURLE_OK;
6936 struct Curl_easy *data = conn->data;
6937
6938 Curl_pgrsTime(data, TIMER_NAMELOOKUP);
6939
6940 if(conn->handler->flags & PROTOPT_NONETWORK) {
6941 /* nothing to setup when not using a network */
6942 *protocol_done = TRUE;
6943 return result;
6944 }
6945 *protocol_done = FALSE; /* default to not done */
6946
6947 /* set proxy_connect_closed to false unconditionally already here since it
6948 is used strictly to provide extra information to a parent function in the
6949 case of proxy CONNECT failures and we must make sure we don't have it
6950 lingering set from a previous invoke */
6951 conn->bits.proxy_connect_closed = FALSE;
6952
6953 /*
6954 * Set user-agent. Used for HTTP, but since we can attempt to tunnel
6955 * basically anything through a http proxy we can't limit this based on
6956 * protocol.
6957 */
6958 if(data->set.str[STRING_USERAGENT]) {
6959 Curl_safefree(conn->allocptr.uagent);
6960 conn->allocptr.uagent =
6961 aprintf("User-Agent: %s\r\n", data->set.str[STRING_USERAGENT]);
6962 if(!conn->allocptr.uagent)
6963 return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
6964 }
6965
6966 data->req.headerbytecount = 0;
6967
6968#ifdef CURL_DO_LINEEND_CONV
6969 data->state.crlf_conversions = 0; /* reset CRLF conversion counter */
6970#endif /* CURL_DO_LINEEND_CONV */
6971
6972 /* set start time here for timeout purposes in the connect procedure, it
6973 is later set again for the progress meter purpose */
6974 conn->now = Curl_tvnow();
6975
6976 if(CURL_SOCKET_BAD == conn->sock[FIRSTSOCKET]) {
6977 conn->bits.tcpconnect[FIRSTSOCKET] = FALSE;
6978 result = Curl_connecthost(conn, conn->dns_entry);
6979 if(result)
6980 return result;
6981 }
6982 else {
6983 Curl_pgrsTime(data, TIMER_CONNECT); /* we're connected already */
6984 Curl_pgrsTime(data, TIMER_APPCONNECT); /* we're connected already */
6985 conn->bits.tcpconnect[FIRSTSOCKET] = TRUE;
6986 *protocol_done = TRUE;
6987 Curl_updateconninfo(conn, conn->sock[FIRSTSOCKET]);
6988 Curl_verboseconnect(conn);
6989 }
6990
6991 conn->now = Curl_tvnow(); /* time this *after* the connect is done, we
6992 set this here perhaps a second time */
6993
6994#ifdef __EMX__
6995 /*
6996 * This check is quite a hack. We're calling _fsetmode to fix the problem
6997 * with fwrite converting newline characters (you get mangled text files,
6998 * and corrupted binary files when you download to stdout and redirect it to
6999 * a file).
7000 */
7001
7002 if((data->set.out)->_handle == NULL) {
7003 _fsetmode(stdout, "b");
7004 }
7005#endif
7006
7007 return result;
7008}
7009
7010CURLcode Curl_connect(struct Curl_easy *data,
7011 struct connectdata **in_connect,
7012 bool *asyncp,
7013 bool *protocol_done)
7014{
7015 CURLcode result;
7016
7017 *asyncp = FALSE; /* assume synchronous resolves by default */
7018
7019 /* call the stuff that needs to be called */
7020 result = create_conn(data, in_connect, asyncp);
7021
7022 if(!result) {
7023 /* no error */
7024 if((*in_connect)->send_pipe.size || (*in_connect)->recv_pipe.size)
7025 /* pipelining */
7026 *protocol_done = TRUE;
7027 else if(!*asyncp) {
7028 /* DNS resolution is done: that's either because this is a reused
7029 connection, in which case DNS was unnecessary, or because DNS
7030 really did finish already (synch resolver/fast async resolve) */
7031 result = Curl_setup_conn(*in_connect, protocol_done);
7032 }
7033 }
7034
7035 if(result == CURLE_NO_CONNECTION_AVAILABLE) {
7036 *in_connect = NULL;
7037 return result;
7038 }
7039
7040 if(result && *in_connect) {
7041 /* We're not allowed to return failure with memory left allocated
7042 in the connectdata struct, free those here */
7043 Curl_disconnect(*in_connect, FALSE); /* close the connection */
7044 *in_connect = NULL; /* return a NULL */
7045 }
7046
7047 return result;
7048}
7049
7050/*
7051 * Curl_init_do() inits the readwrite session. This is inited each time (in
7052 * the DO function before the protocol-specific DO functions are invoked) for
7053 * a transfer, sometimes multiple times on the same Curl_easy. Make sure
7054 * nothing in here depends on stuff that are setup dynamically for the
7055 * transfer.
7056 *
7057 * Allow this function to get called with 'conn' set to NULL.
7058 */
7059
7060CURLcode Curl_init_do(struct Curl_easy *data, struct connectdata *conn)
7061{
7062 struct SingleRequest *k = &data->req;
7063
7064 if(conn)
7065 conn->bits.do_more = FALSE; /* by default there's no curl_do_more() to
7066 * use */
7067
7068 data->state.done = FALSE; /* *_done() is not called yet */
7069 data->state.expect100header = FALSE;
7070
7071 if(data->set.opt_no_body)
7072 /* in HTTP lingo, no body means using the HEAD request... */
7073 data->set.httpreq = HTTPREQ_HEAD;
7074 else if(HTTPREQ_HEAD == data->set.httpreq)
7075 /* ... but if unset there really is no perfect method that is the
7076 "opposite" of HEAD but in reality most people probably think GET
7077 then. The important thing is that we can't let it remain HEAD if the
7078 opt_no_body is set FALSE since then we'll behave wrong when getting
7079 HTTP. */
7080 data->set.httpreq = HTTPREQ_GET;
7081
7082 k->start = Curl_tvnow(); /* start time */
7083 k->now = k->start; /* current time is now */
7084 k->header = TRUE; /* assume header */
7085
7086 k->bytecount = 0;
7087
7088 k->buf = data->state.buffer;
7089 k->hbufp = data->state.headerbuff;
7090 k->ignorebody = FALSE;
7091
7092 Curl_speedinit(data);
7093
7094 Curl_pgrsSetUploadCounter(data, 0);
7095 Curl_pgrsSetDownloadCounter(data, 0);
7096
7097 return CURLE_OK;
7098}

7100/*
7101* get_protocol_family()
7102*
7103* This is used to return the protocol family for a given protocol.
7104*
7105* Parameters:
7106*
7107* protocol [in] - A single bit protocol identifier such as HTTP or HTTPS.
7108*
7109* Returns the family as a single bit protocol identifier.
7110*/
7111
7112static unsigned int get_protocol_family(unsigned int protocol)
7113{
7114 unsigned int family;
7115
7116 switch(protocol) {
7117 case CURLPROTO_HTTP:
7118 case CURLPROTO_HTTPS:
7119 family = CURLPROTO_HTTP;
7120 break;
7121
7122 case CURLPROTO_FTP:
7123 case CURLPROTO_FTPS:
7124 family = CURLPROTO_FTP;
7125 break;
7126
7127 case CURLPROTO_SCP:
7128 family = CURLPROTO_SCP;
7129 break;
7130
7131 case CURLPROTO_SFTP:
7132 family = CURLPROTO_SFTP;
7133 break;
7134
7135 case CURLPROTO_TELNET:
7136 family = CURLPROTO_TELNET;
7137 break;
7138
7139 case CURLPROTO_LDAP:
7140 case CURLPROTO_LDAPS:
7141 family = CURLPROTO_LDAP;
7142 break;
7143
7144 case CURLPROTO_DICT:
7145 family = CURLPROTO_DICT;
7146 break;
7147
7148 case CURLPROTO_FILE:
7149 family = CURLPROTO_FILE;
7150 break;
7151
7152 case CURLPROTO_TFTP:
7153 family = CURLPROTO_TFTP;
7154 break;
7155
7156 case CURLPROTO_IMAP:
7157 case CURLPROTO_IMAPS:
7158 family = CURLPROTO_IMAP;
7159 break;
7160
7161 case CURLPROTO_POP3:
7162 case CURLPROTO_POP3S:
7163 family = CURLPROTO_POP3;
7164 break;
7165
7166 case CURLPROTO_SMTP:
7167 case CURLPROTO_SMTPS:
7168 family = CURLPROTO_SMTP;
7169 break;
7170
7171 case CURLPROTO_RTSP:
7172 family = CURLPROTO_RTSP;
7173 break;
7174
7175 case CURLPROTO_RTMP:
7176 case CURLPROTO_RTMPS:
7177 family = CURLPROTO_RTMP;
7178 break;
7179
7180 case CURLPROTO_RTMPT:
7181 case CURLPROTO_RTMPTS:
7182 family = CURLPROTO_RTMPT;
7183 break;
7184
7185 case CURLPROTO_RTMPE:
7186 family = CURLPROTO_RTMPE;
7187 break;
7188
7189 case CURLPROTO_RTMPTE:
7190 family = CURLPROTO_RTMPTE;
7191 break;
7192
7193 case CURLPROTO_GOPHER:
7194 family = CURLPROTO_GOPHER;
7195 break;
7196
7197 case CURLPROTO_SMB:
7198 case CURLPROTO_SMBS:
7199 family = CURLPROTO_SMB;
7200 break;
7201
7202 default:

7204 break;
7205 }
